ere at (399, 331) with radius ~61 pixels\n# Camera is at (0, 0, -1.5), image plane at z=1\n# A sphere at (0, y, 0) with radius r would project to...\n\n# Let\'s compute the expected sphere position in world coordinates\n# Ray direction for center of sphere:\n# u = 2*(399+0.5)/800 - 1 = -0.00125\n# v = 1 - 2*(331+0.5)/600 = 1 - 1.105 = -0.105\n# Actually let me compute more precisely\n\ncx_pixel = (min_x + max_x) / 2\ncy_pixel = (min_y + max_y) / 2\nprint(f"\\nSphere center pixel: ({cx_pixel:.1f}, {cy_pixel:.1f})")\n\naspect = W / H\nu = (2.0 * (cx_pixel + 0.5) / W - 1.0) * aspect\nv = 1.0 - 2.0 * (cy_pixel + 0.5) / H\nprint(f"Ray direction for sphere center: dir = ({u:.4f}, {v:.4f}, 1)")\n\n# The camera is at (0, 0, -1.5)\n# For a sphere at (0, 0, 0) with radius r, the ray would hit if:\n# (ro + t*rd - center)^2 = r^2\n# For the ray to just touch the sphere at center pixel:\n# t such that the ray passes near the sphere\nEOF\n'] min_timeout_sec: 0.5 max_timeout_sec: 180.0
